', 'status': 'No solution of the pairwise-distinct planar problem is claimed. The literal repetition-allowed syntax has a one-distance witness, but the immutable wording does not determine whether repetitions or overlap are permitted; under the acceptance criteria this semantic fork is a blocking defect.', 'cross_scout_assessment': ['The explicit repeated-point witness, the three-dimensional grid construction, the two-anchor bound, and the fixed-radius incidence lower bound can be checked directly from the supplied arguments; their repetition across reports is not being used as proof.', 'The strongest self-contained planar information supplied is K = Ω(n^(2/3)) for pairwise-distinct sets, while the three-dimensional numerical analogue has K = O(n^(2/3)) for every n.', 'Low-degree curves, bounded unions of lines or circles, parallel-line constructions, cyclic symmetry, and naive orthogonal-axis products are rigorously incompatible with the target scale.', 'The square-lattice benchmark depends on a quantitative count of integers represented by a binary positive-definite quadratic form. That arithmetic theorem is asserted but not fully derived in the reports, so it must be proved or introduced with exact hypotheses before being used.', 'Several reports systematically replace sqrt(log n) by log n in necessary-condition calculations. For the locked target K = o(n/sqrt(log n)), the corrected requirements are: average distance multiplicity ω(n sqrt(log n)), a shell of size ω(sqrt(log n)) around every center, isosceles-triple count ω(n^2 sqrt(log n)), and equal-distance energy ω(n^3 sqrt(log n)).', 'The reports disagree in emphasis rather than in proved conclusions: lattice searches favor arithmetic norm forms; the algebraic-module report proposes a genuinely new high-rank norm mechanism; the matrix reports emphasize low centered rank and Euclidean realizability; and the bisector reports emphasize partial reflection symmetries. These branches should remain separate until one produces a certified lemma.'], 'branch_ranking': [{'rank': 1, 'branch': 'Variable binary quadratic forms and translated lattice cosets', 'assessment': 'Best mathematical fit and easiest to falsify computationally. It directly targets the known norm-collision mechanism, but all finite evidence currently points to only constant-factor changes.'}, {'rank': 2, 'branch': 'Weighted perpendicular-bisector and radial-support lower bounds', 'assessment': 'Highest centrality for a negative result. It exploits interactions among all distance classes, which single-radius incidence bounds discard, but the required improvement from O(n^(7/3)) to O(n^2 sqrt(log n)) is substantial.'}, {'rank': 3, 'branch': 'High-rank algebraic modules and relative norm maps', 'assessment': 'Most novel construction branch and substantively different from planar lattices. Its decisive obligations are uniform norm-value estimates, field-dependent constants, injectivity, and all-n interpolation.'}, {'rank': 4, 'branch': 'Few-symbol Euclidean distance matrices', 'assessment': 'Highly falsifiable at small parameters and capable of discovering nonlattice configurations. Centered rank at most two is only a filter; positive-definite Euclidean compatibility is the main unresolved obstruction.'}, {'rank': 5, 'branch': 'Energy-only lower bounds', 'assessment': 'A clean universal bound E = O(n^3 sqrt(log n)) would settle the distinct planar question negatively, but radial distributions may be too uneven for a second-moment estimate alone. It should be coupled to a multiscale support theorem.'}]}
